{"parentUuid":"41b6a535-8870-4c45-b956-0887cb36f166","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae50cd09b1428afac","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Hr2piNAuJDqcpYd1PpAxtd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01FZZZYdgswvFupEF277rY5g","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"self-improving LLM agents survey verifier evaluator dependency precondition"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6077,"cache_read_input_tokens":6425,"output_tokens":157,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6077},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1003,"output_tokens":157,"cache_read_input_tokens":6425,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6077,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6077,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":8405}}},"requestId":"req_011CcG292YNo7YdK7pr7JmdM","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"fe211706-7b24-4d03-96dd-bdc3890e29e7","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:56.365Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"fe211706-7b24-4d03-96dd-bdc3890e29e7","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"ae50cd09b1428afac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FZZZYdgswvFupEF277rY5g","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"self-improving LLM agents survey verifier evaluator dependency precondition\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Survey on Evaluation of LLM-based Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2503.16416v1\"},{\"title\":\"A Survey of Frontiers in LLM Reasoning: Inference Scaling, Learning to Reason, and Agentic Systems\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.09037\"},{\"title\":\"The Landscape of Agentic Reinforcement Learning for LLMs: A Survey\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.02547\"},{\"title\":\"VerifiAgent: a Unified Verification Agent in Language Model Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.00406\"},{\"title\":\"A Survey on Evaluation of LLM-based Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2503.16416v2\"},{\"title\":\"QuantAgent: Seeking Holy Grail in Trading by Self-Improving Large   Language Model\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.03755\"},{\"title\":\"Plan Verification for LLM-Based Embodied Task Completion Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.02761\"}]\n\nHere are the search results for your query on self-improving LLM agents, survey, verifier, evaluator, dependency, and precondition:\n\nThe search found several highly relevant academic papers:\n\n1. **Survey on Evaluation of LLM-based Agents** - An emerging line of research focuses on whether agents can self-reflect and improve their reasoning through interactive feedback, thereby reducing errors in multi-step interactions.\n\n2. **Verifiers and Refinement** - In scenarios where ground-truth references are unavailable to the agent at test time, agents often rely on verifiers, which are models or systems that provide an approximate measure of correctness, to guide action modifications. The research distinguishes between oracle verifiers which leverage correct answers and have shown significant performance improvements, and non-oracle (or imperfect) verifiers which provide a more widely applicable solution whose form varies depending on the task and knowledge source.\n\n3. **Self-Improvement Mechanisms** - Recent research increasingly emphasizes RL as a mechanism for ongoing reflection, enabling agents to learn from their own mistakes across planning, reasoning, tool use, and memory through iterative, self-generated feedback loops.\n\n4. **Plan Verification Frameworks** - A powerful alternative paradigm involves using LLMs to critique, verify, and refine plans within an iterative loop, often decomposing the problem into distinct agentic roles, as exemplified by the Reflexion framework which splits an agent into an Actor, Evaluator, and Self-Reflection module.\n\nThese results cover multiple aspects of LLM-based agents including evaluation strategies, verification approaches, and self-improvement mechanisms.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"08e0f10f-1a62-4308-afc8-abd060a4fac3","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:03.994Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"self-improving LLM agents survey verifier evaluator dependency precondition","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01XCkL7WUpKGjFpiDRKgcXhJ","content":[{"title":"Survey on Evaluation of LLM-based Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2503.16416v1"},{"title":"A Survey of Frontiers in LLM Reasoning: Inference Scaling, Learning to Reason, and Agentic Systems","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.09037"},{"title":"The Landscape of Agentic Reinforcement Learning for LLMs: A Survey","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.02547"},{"title":"VerifiAgent: a Unified Verification Agent in Language Model Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.00406"},{"title":"A Survey on Evaluation of LLM-based Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2503.16416v2"},{"title":"QuantAgent: Seeking Holy Grail in Trading by Self-Improving Large   Language Model","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2402.03755"},{"title":"Plan Verification for LLM-Based Embodied Task Completion Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.02761"}]},"Here are the search results for your query on self-improving LLM agents, survey, verifier, evaluator, dependency, and precondition:\n\nThe search found several highly relevant academic papers:\n\n1. **Survey on Evaluation of LLM-based Agents** - An emerging line of research focuses on whether agents can self-reflect and improve their reasoning through interactive feedback, thereby reducing errors in multi-step interactions.\n\n2. **Verifiers and Refinement** - In scenarios where ground-truth references are unavailable to the agent at test time, agents often rely on verifiers, which are models or systems that provide an approximate measure of correctness, to guide action modifications. The research distinguishes between oracle verifiers which leverage correct answers and have shown significant performance improvements, and non-oracle (or imperfect) verifiers which provide a more widely applicable solution whose form varies depending on the task and knowledge source.\n\n3. **Self-Improvement Mechanisms** - Recent research increasingly emphasizes RL as a mechanism for ongoing reflection, enabling agents to learn from their own mistakes across planning, reasoning, tool use, and memory through iterative, self-generated feedback loops.\n\n4. **Plan Verification Frameworks** - A powerful alternative paradigm involves using LLMs to critique, verify, and refine plans within an iterative loop, often decomposing the problem into distinct agentic roles, as exemplified by the Reflexion framework which splits an agent into an Actor, Evaluator, and Self-Reflection module.\n\nThese results cover multiple aspects of LLM-based agents including evaluation strategies, verification approaches, and self-improvement mechanisms."],"durationSeconds":7.340516499999911,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"fe211706-7b24-4d03-96dd-bdc3890e29e7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"41b6a535-8870-4c45-b956-0887cb36f166","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"ae50cd09b1428afac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PmLL1ya2YCX8pUDgkc8Lj6","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"AlphaEvolve limitation requires automatic evaluator machine-evaluable domains\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[2506.13131] AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\",\"url\":\"https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2506.13131\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: LLM-Driven Code Evolution\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/alphaevolve-framework\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve | cbarkinozer | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://cbarkinozer.medium.com/alphaevolve-419242a0a4b4\"},{\"title\":\"Google’s AlphaEvolve and the Future of Automated Discovery | by Devansh | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://machine-learning-made-simple.medium.com/googles-alphaevolve-and-the-future-of-automated-discovery-6eb8033879dd\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\",\"url\":\"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"2025-5-16 AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\",\"url\":\"https://msu.dvaoblaka.ru/media/2025/05/68271bf34ef55_AlphaEvolve.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Google’s AlphaEvolve: The AI agent that reclaimed 0.7% of Google’s compute – and how to copy it | VentureBeat\",\"url\":\"https://venturebeat.com/ai/googles-alphaevolve-the-ai-agent-that-reclaimed-0-7-of-googles-compute-and-how-to-copy-it\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind\",\"url\":\"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\"},{\"title\":\"Evolutionary Code Search Beats Humans — The Open Protocol - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/rotiferdev/nvidia-proved-evolutionary-code-search-beats-humans-heres-what-an-open-protocol-for-it-looks-like-1b0e\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about AlphaEvolve's limitation regarding automatic evaluators and machine-evaluable domains:\n\nThe main limitation of AlphaEvolve is that it handles problems for which it is possible to devise an automated evaluator. More specifically, the current critical constraint for AlphaEvolve is the need for a human-defined, machine-executable evaluation function.\n\nBecause problems in mathematics, computer science, and system optimization typically permit automated evaluation metrics, the efforts on AlphaEvolve focus on these domains. This constraint means that problems requiring manual experimentation or \"wet-lab\" feedback are currently out of scope for this specific approach.\n\nIn practical terms, enterprises should look first at workflows where \"better\" is a quantifiable number the system can compute – be it latency, cost, error rate or throughput. However, there are potential future directions: LLMs are increasingly capable of scaffolding approximate evaluators from sparse, noisy, or even natural language inputs, where a domain expert can describe what matters in vague terms, and the model can produce an initial, code-executable version of it.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"20dc6a12-7873-4b0b-b03f-88d7ecf7cf89","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:04.424Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"AlphaEvolve limitation requires automatic evaluator machine-evaluable domains","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01DDgiwrd6T5bwisBmaMhgEb","content":[{"title":"[2506.13131] AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery","url":"https://ar5iv.labs.arxiv.org/html/2506.13131"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: LLM-Driven Code Evolution","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/t