{"parentUuid":"84faa8e1-953d-4653-b09d-cf03ed0ca329","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"ae50cd09b1428afac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GygERMhqyRj6R7oLWfhfgu","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"AlphaEvolve critique only works where solutions machine-evaluable verifier required essay\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve | cbarkinozer | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://cbarkinozer.medium.com/alphaevolve-419242a0a4b4\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: How Google's New AI Aims For Truth With Self-correction - Dataconomy\",\"url\":\"https://dataconomy.com/2025/05/15/alphaevolve-how-googles-new-ai-aims-for-truth-with-self-correction/\"},{\"title\":\"Google’s AlphaEvolve and the Future of Automated Discovery | by Devansh | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://machine-learning-made-simple.medium.com/googles-alphaevolve-and-the-future-of-automated-discovery-6eb8033879dd\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind\",\"url\":\"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\"},{\"title\":\"[Literature Review] AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\",\"url\":\"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/alphaevolve-a-coding-agent-for-scientific-and-algorithmic-discovery\"},{\"title\":\"Mathematical exploration and discovery at scale\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.02864\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve on Google Cloud | Google Cloud Blog\",\"url\":\"https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/ai-machine-learning/alphaevolve-on-google-cloud/\"},{\"title\":\"Paper Review: AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery | by Andrew Lukyanenko | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://artgor.medium.com/paper-review-alphaevolve-a-coding-agent-for-scientific-and-algorithmic-discovery-5732a876c2e2\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding AlphaEvolve's limitation with machine-evaluable verifiers:\n\nAlphaEvolve requires that solutions be machine-evaluable—if something can't be machine-evaluated, it doesn't count, and it can only operate in domains where evaluation can be formalized. This includes math, systems optimization, hardware design, and algorithm tuning, but not poetry.\n\nThis is a fundamental constraint of the system. The system operates on problems where potential solutions can be automatically and programmatically evaluated. The primary limitation is the requirement for an automated evaluator.\n\nThe reasoning behind this requirement is that AlphaEvolve relies on a strict, executable evaluation function defined by the user—a \"truth oracle\" that returns scalar scores defining success, and if it can't be machine-evaluated, it doesn't count. This design allows AlphaEvolve to avoid relying on LLM judgment, which can hallucinate, but it comes at the cost of being limited to domains where objective evaluation metrics can be formally defined.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"d9542c37-6e72-4385-a023-6f8d37f758e0","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:30.838Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"AlphaEvolve critique only works where solutions machine-evaluable verifier required essay","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01BN8djuzBPoQeMJ27fYJe7h","content":[{"title":"AlphaEvolve | cbarkinozer | Medium","url":"https://cbarkinozer.medium.com/alphaevolve-419242a0a4b4"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: How Google's New AI Aims For Truth With Self-correction - Dataconomy","url":"https://dataconomy.com/2025/05/15/alphaevolve-how-googles-new-ai-aims-for-truth-with-self-correction/"},{"title":"Google’s AlphaEvolve and the Future of Automated Discovery | by Devansh | Medium","url":"https://machine-learning-made-simple.medium.com/googles-alphaevolve-and-the-future-of-automated-discovery-6eb8033879dd"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind","url":"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/"},{"title":"[Literature Review] AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery","url":"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/alphaevolve-a-coding-agent-for-scientific-and-algorithmic-discovery"},{"title":"Mathematical exploration and discovery at scale","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.02864"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve on Google Cloud | Google Cloud Blog","url":"https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/ai-machine-learning/alphaevolve-on-google-cloud/"},{"title":"Paper Review: AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery | by Andrew Lukyanenko | Medium","url":"https://artgor.medium.com/paper-review-alphaevolve-a-coding-agent-for-scientific-and-algorithmic-discovery-5732a876c2e2"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding AlphaEvolve's limitation with machine-evaluable verifiers:\n\nAlphaEvolve requires that solutions be machine-evaluable—if something can't be machine-evaluated, it doesn't count, and it can only operate in domains where evaluation can be formalized. This includes math, systems optimization, hardware design, and algorithm tuning, but not poetry.\n\nThis is a fundamental constraint of the system. The system operates on problems where potential solutions can be automatically and programmatically evaluated. The primary limitation is the requirement for an automated evaluator.\n\nThe reasoning behind this requirement is that AlphaEvolve relies on a strict, executable evaluation function defined by the user—a \"truth oracle\" that returns scalar scores defining success, and if it can't be machine-evaluated, it doesn't count. This design allows AlphaEvolve to avoid relying on LLM judgment, which can hallucinate, but it comes at the cost of being limited to domains where objective evaluation metrics can be formally defined."],"durationSeconds":7.096104165999219,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"84faa8e1-953d-4653-b09d-cf03ed0ca329","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"f0c82626-620a-4775-9994-d1f01a388ccc","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"ae50cd09b1428afac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01K5r5ft49PvEUNE5n3oMXry","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"recursive self-improvement bounded by base model verification ceiling lesswrong\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[1312.6764] Bounded Recursive Self-Improvement\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1312.6764\"},{\"title\":\"Self-Improvement in Language Models: The Sharpening Mechanism\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.01951\"},{\"title\":\"\\\"Recursive Self-Improvement\\\" Is Three Different Things\",\"url\":\"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/XHd75cuHhWcBDd8to/recursive-self-improvement-is-three-different-things\"},{\"title\":\"Why all the fuss about recursive self-improvement?\",\"url\":\"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/8NKu9WES7KeKRWEKK/why-all-the-fuss-about-recursive-self-improvement\"},{\"title\":\"Traffic matrix estimation with the QSP-MLE model and recursive improvement\",\"url\":\"https://image-ppubs.uspto.gov/dirsearch-public/print/downloadPdf/12542725\"},{\"title\":\"Recursive Self-Improvement, Without the Hype | Nicolas Schneider - Data Scientist / Developer\",\"url\":\"https://nicolas2912.github.io/2025/09/24/recursive-self-improvement.html\"},{\"title\":\"A Formulation of Recursive Self-Improvement and Its Possible Efficiency\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1805.06610\"},{\"title\":\"Recursive self-improvement — Grokipedia\",\"url\":\"https://grokipedia.com/page/Recursive_self-improvement\"},{\"title\":\"LADDER: Self-Improving LLMs Through Recursive Problem Decomposition\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.00735\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found several relevant sources discussing recursive self-improvement and related concepts:\n\n## Key Findings\n\n**Bounded Recursive Self-Improvement:**\nOne foundational work describes a system that achieves recursive self-improvement after it leaves the lab, within the boundaries imposed by its designers.\n\n**Recent LessWrong Discussion:**\n\"Recursive self-improvement\" is described as load-bearing ambiguous in AI risk discourse, referring to at least three qualitatively different processes that differ in mechanism, speed, observability, bottlenecks, governance implications, and timeline relevance. One observable type involves better orchestration leading to better task decomposition and better use of existing cognition, where the same base model is wrapped in better scaffolding.\n\n**Base Model Verification:**\nSelf-improvement can be viewed as using the model as its own verifier to improve generation and sharpen the model toward high-quality responses. Recent work on self-improvement in language models emphasizes models directing their own learning trajectory by generating and solving progressively more challenging problems, requiring only a formal verifier rather than human guidance.\n\n**Limitations and Constraints:**\nSemi-autonomous validation is expected to mature with formal checks and high-throughput labs, with local recursive self-improvement cells in narrow toolchains, still bounded by goals, governance, and physics.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"0449d6de-a4d6-478a-92e5-9d8c74d09e2f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:32.898Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"recursive self-improvement bounded by base model verification ceiling lesswrong","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_017sJrRWhksP4R6xdFQBrL8e","content":[{"title":"[1312.6764] Bounded Recursive Self-Improvement","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/1312.6764"},{"title":"Self-Improvement in Language Models: The Sharpening Mechanism","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.01951"},{"title":"\"Recursive Self-Improvement\" Is Three Different Things","url":"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/XHd75cuHhWcBDd8to/recursive-self-improvement-is-