 task decomposition → better use of existing cognition → emergent competence gains,\" but it does not explicitly argue that such improvements are fundamentally bounded by base model limits.\n\nSimilarly, while the article mentions bottlenecks for Type 2 (R&D-Level Improvement), it does not frame these as preconditions involving verifiers or evaluators.\n\nThe closest relevant quote addresses Type 1's mechanism: \"You wrap the same base model in better scaffolding and suddenly it can do things it couldn't do before. No algorithmic breakthrough required.\" However, this describes what happens rather than arguing capability boundaries.\n\nThe webpage content does not contain the specific argumentative claims you're requesting.","durationMs":7685,"url":"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/XHd75cuHhWcBDd8to/recursive-self-improvement-is-three-different-things"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"fff8b713-82a3-4340-a9b4-a84215fe1ae7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
