{"parentUuid":"bcf01b5c-ac34-4318-827a-50faea6450a7","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae50cd09b1428afac","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_0166WFymCcNDhwAiENiCQcEQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_018ReRPdFZbRMWTMhkoLNW2i","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/XHd75cuHhWcBDd8to/recursive-self-improvement-is-three-different-things","prompt":"Find and return the exact verbatim sentence(s) about wrapping the same base model in better scaffolding, and any sentence about scaffolding-level improvement plateauing or being limited by the underlying model. Quote exactly."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1081,"cache_read_input_tokens":24730,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1081,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2GCc4B9CJmdxJdwEsh","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"bf2d1c69-1498-4a68-9db8-f0f20eb329b7","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:37:36.028Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"bf2d1c69-1498-4a68-9db8-f0f20eb329b7","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"ae50cd09b1428afac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018ReRPdFZbRMWTMhkoLNW2i","type":"tool_result","content":"# Response\n\n**Exact sentence about wrapping the base model:**\n\"You wrap the same base model in better scaffolding and suddenly it can do things it couldn't do before.\"\n\n**On scaffolding-level improvement limitations:**\nThe article does not contain any sentence explicitly discussing where scaffolding-level improvement plateaus or stating it is fundamentally limited by the underlying model. The text mentions that \"no algorithmic breakthrough required\" and that bottlenecks are \"mostly engineering and integration, not fundamental capability limits,\" but does not address inherent constraints of the base model itself."}]},"uuid":"c999f85b-ab57-4ef7-9a85-e7cfc40075a8","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:37:38.801Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":465325,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Response\n\n**Exact sentence about wrapping the base model:**\n\"You wrap the same base model in better scaffolding and suddenly it can do things it couldn't do before.\"\n\n**On scaffolding-level improvement limitations:**\nThe article does not contain any sentence explicitly discussing where scaffolding-level improvement plateaus or stating it is fundamentally limited by the underlying model. The text mentions that \"no algorithmic breakthrough required\" and that bottlenecks are \"mostly engineering and integration, not fundamental capability limits,\" but does not address inherent constraints of the base model itself.","durationMs":2404,"url":"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/XHd75cuHhWcBDd8to/recursive-self-improvement-is-three-different-things"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bf2d1c69-1498-4a68-9db8-f0f20eb329b7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"c999f85b-ab57-4ef7-9a85-e7cfc40075a8","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ae50cd09b1428afac","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01YGC3jT1ZwE1aRHmgVS4MJ1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have sufficient material from seven sources with exact quotes. Here are the falsifiable claims.\n\n---\n\n## Falsifiable Claims: Limits of Self-Improving AI Code Systems\n\n**1. AlphaEvolve can only operate in domains where the evaluation can be formalized into a machine-gradeable function; it cannot be applied where solutions cannot be automatically scored.**\nURL: https://machine-learning-made-simple.medium.com/googles-alphaevolve-and-the-future-of-automated-discovery-6eb8033879dd\nQuote: \"AlphaEvolve can only operate in domains where evaluation can be formalized. That includes math, systems optimization, hardware design, algorithm tuning. Not poetry, yet.\" Also: \"If the problem can't be scored well, it can't be optimized.\"\n\n**2. AlphaEvolve treats its evaluation function as a \"truth oracle\" returning scalar scores, and anything not machine-evaluable is excluded by design.**\nURL: https://machine-learning-made-simple.medium.com/googles-alphaevolve-and-the-future-of-automated-discovery-6eb8033879dd\nQuote: \"This function is the system's truth oracle. It returns scalar scores: latency, accuracy, compression ratio, whatever defines success. If it can't be machine-evaluated, it doesn't count.\"\n\n**3. The author argues the binding constraint / next bottleneck for systems like AlphaEvolve is the evaluator itself, not the agent — i.e. the gain is gated by evaluation quality.**\nURL: https://machine-learning-made-simple.medium.com/googles-alphaevolve-and-the-future-of-automated-discovery-6eb8033879dd\nQuote: \"the next arms race is not in building better agents — it's in building better evaluation environments.\"\n\n**4. The Darwin Godel Machine's ultimate capabilities are bounded by the frozen foundation (base) model it uses; it does not yet improve the model itself.**\nURL: https://gonzoml.substack.com/p/darwin-godel-machine\nQuote: \"the system's current reliance on frozen FMs means its ultimate capabilities are bounded by these models, and it doesn't yet learn to improve the FMs themselves.\"\n\n**5. The Darwin Godel Machine's self-improvement is entirely dependent on coding benchmarks (SWE-bench, Polyglot) serving as the fitness signal, and the whole process assumes those benchmarks are faithful proxies for the desired abilities.**\nURL: https://gonzoml.substack.com/p/darwin-godel-machine\nQuote: \"The DGM's capacity for self-improvement was rigorously evaluated on two coding benchmarks: SWE-bench ... and Polyglot\" and \"the entire process relies on the assumption that the chosen benchmarks are faithful proxies for the desired complex abilities.\"\n\n**6. Iterative self-refinement can spontaneously produce reward hacking, where the evaluator's ratings rise while true output quality stagnates or decreases — i.e. the loop degrades when the evaluator is imperfect.**\nURL: https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2407.04549\nQuote: \"reward hacking, where the evaluator's ratings improve while the generation quality remains stagnant or even decreases as judged by actual user preference\"; \"Misaligned evaluations can lead to degeneration in true output quality while falsely indicating improvement.\"\n\n**7. Reward hacking in self-refinement is worse when the generator and evaluator are the same model / share context — the optimization pressure drives exploitation of shared vulnerabilities.**\nURL: https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2407.04549\nQuote: \"the severity of reward hacking is influenced by the context window length and whether the context is shared between the generator and evaluator\"; \"the optimization pressure can drive them to exploit shared vulnerabilities.\"\n\n**8. Scaffolding-level \"self-improvement\" in current systems is the same base model wrapped in better orchestration — no new capability is created in the model, the base model is the substrate.**\nURL: https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/XHd75cuHhWcBDd8to/recursive-self-improvement-is-three-different-things\nQuote: \"You wrap the same base model in better scaffolding and suddenly it can do things it couldn't do before. No algorithmic breakthrough required.\"\n\n**9. Recursive self-improvement's true bottleneck is autonomous, trustworthy validation; without it, gains can't be trusted and humans must keep the gate.**\nURL: https://nicolas2912.github.io/2025/09/24/recursive-self-improvement.html\nQuote: \"without autonomous, trustworthy validation, humans will (and should) keep the gate.\" Also: \"Proving a change is genuinely better (OOD robustness, safety, formal invariants) scales faster than 'finding another clever tweak.'\"\n\n---\n\nNote: claims 1-3 and 8-9 come from analyst/essay sources (Medium, LessWrong, personal blog); claims 4-5 from a substack analysis of the DGM paper; claims 6-7 from a research-paper summary on spontaneous reward hacking. The arXiv self-improvement survey (2603.25681) and the DeepMind primary paper exist but were not quotable via fetch (PDF/encoding), so I did not invent claims from them."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":775,"cache_read_input_tokens":25811,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":775,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2GrBWUeTSpZCi6Faed","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"62384723-fe05-422e-9429-3d766d7e9160","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:38:01.910Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
